{{Infobox organization | name = Le Cercle des Gourmettes | image = | image_size = | caption = | motto = | formation = 1929 | founder = Paulette Edlinger | status = Disbanded | purpose = Gourmet food appreciation | location = Paris | membership = Exclusive | language = French | key_people = [[Julia Child]], [[Simone Beck]], [[Louisette Bertholle]]}}
'''Le Cercle des Gourmettes''' was an exclusive club or "circle" of women in [[Paris]] devoted to [[Gourmet|gourmet food]]. The circle was started in 1929 by an American, Paulette Edlinger, and the name may have been a [[bon mot]] in protest of the non-feminine form of the word ''gourmet''.<ref>See ''Le Trésor de la Langue Française Informatisé'', where ''gourmet'' is a masculine noun meaning ''foodie'', but ''gourmette'' is a feminine word for ''bling'' or ''bracelet''. </ref><ref>{{Citation | last =Guagnini | first =Enrico | title =Gourmettes | journal =Grand Gourmet | date =September 1996 | language = Italian}} reprinted in {{Citation | last =Guagnini | first =Enrico | title =LE GOUREMETTES CAMBIANO DIZIONARIO | journal =Bolgher News | volume =2 | issue =12 | pages =4 | date =April 11, 2010 | language =Italian | url =http://www.nextec.it/bolgherinews/bolgherinewsn12.pdf}}</ref>
The club began at a time of economic prosperity just prior to the [[Great Depression in France]]. It was started by the wives of members of [[Club des Cent]] and convened on alternate Fridays to enjoy lunches and dinners at the electric company headquarters in Paris, Electricité et Gaz.<ref>{{cite book | last =Child | first =Julia | last2 = Prud'homme | first2 = Alex | title =[[My Life in France]] | publisher =Anchor Books (Knoph Doubleday) | date =2006 | location =New York | pages =133}}</ref> The club's most famous members were [[Julia Child]], [[Simone Beck]], and [[Louisette Bertholle]]. Each joined the club in the late 1940s.
Versions of the club later existed in Canada and Switzerland.
