{{for|the "Orang Ulu" of the [[Malay Peninsula]] [[Orang Asli]]|Jakun people}} [[File:YanAriefSapeh.jpg|thumb|right|Two Dayak Orang Ulu men from [[Sarawak]], [[Malaysia]], playing the [[sapeh]].]] '''Orang Ulu''' ("people of the interior" in [[Malay language|Malay]]) is an ethnic designation politically coined to group together roughly 27 very small but ethnically diverse tribal groups in northeastern [[Sarawak]], [[Malaysia]]<ref name="faq">{{cite web|url=http://www.faqs.org/minorities/South-East-Asia/Orang-Ulu-of-Sarawak.html |title=Orang Ulu of Sarawak |publisher=Internet FAQ Archives |accessdate=2016-08-03}}</ref> with populations ranging from less than 300 persons to over 25,000 persons. ''Orang Ulu'' is not a legal term, and no such racial group exists or is listed in the [[Malaysia]]n Constitution. The term was popularised by the Orang Ulu National Association (OUNA), which was formed in 1969.
The Orang Ulu tribal groups are diverse, they typically live in [[longhouse]]s elaborately decorated with murals and woodcarvings.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jeffrey Jalong|title=Kalong: Seni Motif Tradisi Orang Ulu|year=2001|publisher=Kementerian Kebudayaan Kesenian dan Pelancongan Malaysia|isbn=967-903-035-0}}</ref> They are also well known for their intricate [[beadwork]] detailed [[tattoo]]s, rattan weaving, and other tribal crafts.<ref name="patriciahului">{{cite web|url=http://seeds.theborneopost.com/2016/05/25/dying-tradition-of-orangulu-rattan-weaving/ |title=Dying Tradition of Orang Ulu Rattan Weaving |publisher=The Borneo Post |author=Patricia Hului |date=2016-05-25 |accessdate=2016-08-03}}</ref> The Orang Ulu tribes can also be identified by their unique music - distinctive sounds from their [[Sapeh|sapes]], a plucked boat-shaped lute, formerly with two strings, nowadays usually with four strings.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jeffrey Jalong|title=Sape: Seni Muzik Terbilang Orang Ulu Sarawak|year=2007|publisher=|isbn=}}</ref> They also practice ''Kanjet'', a form of traditional dance.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jeffrey Jalong|title=Kanjet: Seni Tarian Tradisional Orang Ulu Sarawak|year=2012|publisher=Jabatan Kebudayaan dan Kesenian Negara|isbn=967-5552-22-0}}</ref>
A vast majority of the Orang Ulu tribes are [[Christian]]s, but old traditional religions are still practiced in some areas.
==Orang Ulu classification== There are about 27 small [[Dayak people]] groups that are classified as Orang Ulu such as:- * ''[[Apo Kayan people]]'' ** [[Kenyah people]]<ref name="faq"/> *** Kajang<ref name="erivina"/><ref name="wendyhutton"/> **** Kajaman<ref name="nizam"/> **** Lahanan<ref name="erivina"/> **** Sian<ref name="wendyhutton"/> *** [[Penan]]<ref name="wendyhutton">{{cite book|author=Wendy Hutton|title=Adventure Guides: East Malaysia|year=2000|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|page=130|isbn=962-593-180-5}}</ref> *** Sebop<ref name="nizam">{{cite web|url=http://www.thepatriots.my/orang-ulu/ |title=ORANG ULU |publisher=The Patriots |author=Nizam GTZ |accessdate=2016-08-03}}</ref> ** [[Kayan people (Borneo)]]<ref name="faq"/> * [[Bidayuh]]<ref name="faq"/> ** [[Kendayan people|Kendayan]]<ref name="faq"/> ** [[Ukit people]]<ref name="patriciahului"/><ref name="wendyhutton"/> * [[Murut people]]<ref name="faq"/> ** Tagol<ref name="wendyhutton"/> * [[Punan]]<ref name="faq"/> ** Lisum<ref name="wendyhutton"/> * ''Apo Duat'' ** [[Kelabit people]]<ref name="faq"/> ***Berawan<ref name="erivina">{{cite web|url=http://sarawaktourism.com/blog/our-people-orang-ulu/ |title=Our People - Orang Ulu |publisher=Sarawak Tourism |author=Erivina |accessdate=2016-08-03}}</ref> **** Kiput<ref name="nizam"/> ** [[Lun Bawang]]<ref name="wendyhutton"/> ** [[Sa'ban people]]<ref>{{cite book|author=Frans Welman|title=Borneo Trilogy Sarawak: Volume 2|year=2011|publisher=Booksmango|page=138|isbn=616-245-089-9}}</ref>
